We get EMs for both USL PL & Virtual PL H&S dropouts if a USL Firewall goes down for the count.  Most likely the USL Firewall Cable reseat triggered a network traffic jam.  I suspect virtual PLs that route their H&S through both Node 2 & USL Firewalls backed up traffic on the Node 2 Firewall, causing the ER3 PL H&S dropouts.

Author:McMurray, Ethan M.Columbus loss of Lateral Transfer and PL Command Capability

Failure: CLSW (Columbus LAN Switch) failure. Potentially overloaded due to an unexpected connection to the JSL network and/or a radiation hit in the SAA.

Impact: No impacts to NASA payloads. ESA has lost the nominal commanding layer in the Columbus, however they can still command at the vital layer. This is a similar to the configuration last weekend (ref. PRO log 2377460), however this time they also do not have a functioning CLSW.

Workaround: Troubleshooting is currently ongoing. PLUTO disabled ports 19 and 20 on Node 2 Router Switch A per FN 108439B. Overheard on COL FDIR loop that port disablement didn't immediately fix the problem and they are working to plan a CLSW power cycle.

COL Flight reported to Flight that they've lost connection into several components onboard including the DMC, MMU, and CLSW. As a result, STRATOS is unable to perform the aforementioned steps to attempt a recovery of Lateral Transfer services.

STRATOS believes that the root cause is a LAN switch failure due to it being overloaded by an unexpected connection to the JSL network. STRATOS worked with PLUTO on a forward plan. PLUTO disabled ports 19 and 20 on Node 2 Router Switch A (ref. Flight Note 108439B).

Log / Entry:PRO REAL-TIME LOG / 2378718Category:Data AnomalyAction:ErrorFlags:Handover Item, EXPRESS Ops Lead, PRO Tech Lead, New AR
Author:Norris, John O.Extended, Sporadic Payload H&S Data Anomaly

AR 10362 Generated by POD

FAILURE: No definitive theories at this time.
IMPACT: Intermittent loss of H&S from all non KU-IP Sub-rack payloads, and Express Rack Laptop's Alive Indicators. Impact duration: Approx. 1 hour, 39 minutes.
WORKAROUND: Issue stopped on its own accord during an LOS, still investigating.

Initial signature
23:24:17 - [EM]- Polar 4 H&S Data is stale
23:24:17 - [EM]- ICEBERG 1 H&S Data is stale
23:24:20 - [EM]- SABL1 H&S Data is stale
23:24:20 - [EM]- SABL 2 H&S Data is stale

These Payloads continued to go in and out for about 5 minutes before other payloads eventually began experiencing H&S drop outs.
EMs continued to snowball from an increasing number of payloads.
We never received any corrupt Rack H&S messages in PLEV.

Impacted payloads:
ICEBERG 1
POLAR 4
SABL1
SABL2
AMS Laptop
GLACIER 5
MUSES Server
POLAR 7
GLACIER 2
SAMS CU
SAMS RTS D1
SAMS RTS D2
Plant Habitat
ICEBERG 2
LIDAL-ALTEA
POLAR 1


Also intermittently lost the following Express Laptop Computer (ELC) Laptop alive Indicators:
ELC 2
ELC 4
ELC 5
ELC 6
ELC 7
ELC 8

Troubleshooting and Coordination Events:
CRONUS confirmed that their systems are nominal.
PRO1 contacted Tech and Express leads. Express rack H&S still looks good. EOL and Tech think that this is a data issue.
Checked GEDI Gateway Ping with DMC - No issues found. DMC Leaning towards network related issue.
STRATOS also reported issues with ESA payload connections on COL Flight
Team suspects JSL issue. PLUTO being called in.

We went AOS at ~01:03 and have not received additional EMs, payload data appears to be in nominal state again.
Anomaly duration was approximately 1 hour, 39 minutes.
DMC network specialists noticed data spike around the time of initial signature, they will be in contact with PLUTO to investigate.
C&DH MER checked in on POIC on DMC loop, PRO 1 reported that we were no longer experiencing H&S drop outs.

Theory behind anomaly at time of writing:
PLUTO reported data surge in firewalls and high CPU usage on primary firewall. This is associated with a data spike.
Express Racks network interface likely got overwhelmed with high network traffic and had issues processing all requests in and out of the rack, leading to H&S dropouts from sub rack payloads.

Checked in with STRATOS, they reported Issues with ASTRO PI 1 & 2 loosing connection. Anomaly duration for ESA Payloads coincided with POIC.
CANSEI reported no issues with any JAXA payloads.

Log / Entry:PRO REAL-TIME LOG / 2379136Category:SPARTANAction:StatusFlags:PREP PRO, ELC Ops Lead, Real Time PRO Lead
Author:Depatie, David D.RPCM S33A_E Trip Troubleshooting - AR 010365
Continuation of PRO Log #2379120

On GMT 289 Orbit 3, we received several Advisories for a trip on RPCM S33A_E. SPARTAN confirmed that RPC 3 on this RPCM is the one that tripped. This is an external RPCM. A breakdown of the loads are as follows:

RPC 1: ELC 2 Aux RPC
RPC 2: AMS Aux RPC
RPC 3: ESP-3(External Spare Platform) Secondary Heaters
RPC 4: ELC 4 Aux RPC

SPARTAN's analysis showed that there was no overcurrent on the RPC 3 and they would like to attempt to reclose it. They called Marshall PRO and asked what the current power configuration for AMS was. Per the timeline, AMS is operating in their split power configuration utilizing 800 W on their Main RPC and 800 W on their Aux RPC. SPARTAN was curious because they said there is small chance that when they attempt the re-closure of the RPC 3, that the RPCM S33A_E may experience a Power on Reset, impacting all of the other downstream loads on the RPCM. SPARTAN wanted to know what impacts AMS would have in the event of a power loss on their Aux RPC.

I asked the AMS PD how long it would take for them to reconfigure their payload to operate only on Main power in the event of this failure. AMS states that an unexpected loss of their AUX RPC would result in a science loss and they would need to call in a specialist to reconfigure their payload to operate on Main only. It would take them approximately 2 hours for the specialist to come in and complete the transition to Main only power and get back to taking science nominally again.

Other impacts to an RPCM S33A_E Power on Reset would be a loss of operational power for ELC 2 ExPA 2 (MISSE-FF) and ELC 4 ExPA 1 (MUSES), as well as ELC 2 PM-2 Heaters and ELC 4 PM-2 Heaters.

Per FR B19-18 for MISSE-FF:

"FOR INTERRUPTION OF THE AUXILIARY POWER CHANNEL ON ELC-2.
THIS WILL RESULT IN A LOSS OF EXPA-2 120V OPERATIONAL POWER AND LOSS OF ONE SURVIVAL HEATER (PM2 CHANNEL 8). MISSE-FF HAS SURVIVAL HEATERS POWERED BY THE PM1 CHANNEL 8. AS LONG AS THESE SURVIVAL HEATERS ARE ON, THERE ARE NO THERMAL CONSTRAINTS ON MISSE-FF."

Per FR B19-18 for MUSES:

"FOR INTERRUPTION OF AUXILIARY POWER TO EXPRESS LOGISTIC CARRIER 4:
AS LONG AS SURVIVAL HEATERS (PM)-1 CHANNEL 11 ARE POWERED, THERE ARE NO THERMAL CONSTRAINTS."

Per FR B19-18 for NICER:
"FOR INTERRUPTION OF AUXILIARY POWER TO EXPRESS LOGISTIC CARRIER 2:
NICER MAY NEED TO HAVE THE EXPRESS LOGISTICS CARRIER-2 EXPA-1 DISCRETE CHANNELS 1 AND 2 UNPOWERED BY THE POIC TO PROVIDE HEATER POWER THROUGH THE 120VDC OPERATIONAL HEATERS DEPENDING ON TEMPERATURE TRENDING WHILE POWER IS OFF. THE NICER PD MAY NEED TO PLACE THE NICER PAYLOAD INTO A THERMALLY SAFE HEADS DOWN OR STOW CONFIGURATION, 28VDC OPERATIONAL POWER REMOVED, AND DISCRETE CHANNELS 4 AND/OR 5 DEACTIVATED IF THE POWER OUTAGE WILL BE LONGER THAN 1 HOUR DEPENDING ON TEMPERATURE TRENDING WHILE POWER IS OFF. IF LESS THAN ONE HOUR, THEN NICER PAYLOAD WILL BE ABLE TO CONTINUE OPERATING AND COLLECTING SCIENCE IN THIS MODE. IF NICER IS TO BE PLACED IN THE HEADS DOWN POSITION, POIC SHOULD NOTIFY MCC-H.
PER RULE {B19-59} PARAGRAPH D, WHICH DOCUMENTS ACCEPTABLE ISS EVENTS AND ATTITUDE CONTROL MODES FOR ALL NICER CONFIGURATIONS."

Per FR B19-18 for SAGE:
"FOR INTERRUPTION OF AUXILIARY POWER TO EXPRESS LOGISTIC CARRIER 4:
THERE ARE NO THERMAL CONSTRAINTS, AS LONG AS, THE 120VDC CONTINGENCY HEATER (PM-1 CHANNEL 12) OR THE 120 VDC OPERATIONAL AND 28 VDC OPERATIONAL POWER REMAIN ON."

Confirmed via the ELC 2 and 4 Nominal Commanding displays that ELC 2 PM-1 channel 8 and ELC 4 PM-1 channel 11 are powered, so we would not start any thermal clocks for MISSE-FF or MUSES per the Flight Rule, however, MUSES and MISSE-FF would likely have science impacts from losing their Operational power. Confirmed SAGE has their 120V and 28V operational power enabled and PM-1 channel 12 heater power enabled via the ELC 4 Nominal Commanding display. NICER may require PRO commanding to provide additional heaters through their operational power and may need to command their payload into a thermally safe heads down or stow configuration to avoid thermal impacts.

After discussing impacts with SPARTAN and AMS, the team decided to forego any immediate troubleshooting since there is no urgent need to close the ESP RPC 3 on RPCM S33A_E, and the potential impacts should a Power on Reset occur would cause a loss of science for multiple payloads. Forward action it to get the Increment teams involved to create a forward action plan for the re-closure of RPC 3 on RPCM S33A_E. SPARTAN opened AR 010365 to document the anomaly.

Flagging PREP PRO and Externals Lead. Please coordinate with the IL SPARTAN, MISSE-FF, MUSES, NICER and AMS PDs to create a forward plan for the re-closure of RPC 3 on RPCM S33A_E.

Log / Entry:PRO REAL-TIME LOG / 2379848Category:AMSAction:ConfigurationFlags:PD CMD, Handover Item, ELC Ops Lead
Author:Aaron, Logan C.AMS Reconfiguration for RPCM Troubleshooting

AMS had previously configured to a 100/0 power distribution on the 4B power channel in preparation for the RPCM S3_3A_E RPC 3 re-closure troubleshooting.
AMS was under the impression that this troubleshooting would be happening fairly quickly and that they would not be in this configuration for very long.
Due to being in this power configuration as well as the current beta angle AMS is seeing an increase in temperature of their power distribution system and would like to revert back to their nominal 50/50 power distribution until 19:20 (GMT 293) when they will be performing some internal reconfiguration in support of the 78P redocking on GMT 295. This internal config will better support the 100/0 4B power distribution. AMS is okay with staying in this configuration until GMT 295/0900. The troubleshooting is potentially being planned for (GMT 294).

Coordinated with SPARTAN and they are in support of this plan.
POD gave a "GO" for AMS power reconfig.
~14:45 - AMS reported that they are back in the 50/50 power distribution config

After continuing to coordinate with SPARTAN to work a plan they have informed us that the risk window for the potential impacts of a Power on Reset after the RPC re-closure do not exist purely during the troubleshooting process, however it was decided to have AMS in the 100/0 4B power distribution configuration for this first troubleshooting attempt as contingency. The risk window for a Power on Reset exist for hours, days, or months even after a successful re-closure attempt due to the nature of this failure. Historically, a Power on Reset has been seen within the first few days after the re-closure.

SPARTAN was interested in the maximum amount of time that AMS could remain purely on the 4B power channel. AMS reports that after the 78P redocking on GMT 295 they will be returning to their nominal internal configuration and will not be returning to the reduced power internal configuration until GMT 303 in preparation for the 79P docking. This configuration potentially offers another troubleshooting window. AMS suggest proceeding with the re-closure asap after 19:20 (GMT 293) when their internal reconfig is complete.


~18:45 - AMS received the Go from POD/Flight to reconfigure their power distribution to 100% on 4B.
19:18 - AMS reported they their reconfiguration is complete

Marking for EOL/PRO Tech Lead/RT PRO Lead for awareness.
I think perhaps there is more to the JSL 14 updates that may not be reflected by our under the glass document.

EOL was on console performing checkout of the laptop, so we did not shut down the laptop when the current draw went above 3.5A.  Current draw dropped to below 0.2A right after EOL checked off console.  Since brick already tripped, we needed to cycle the SSPCM channel to reset the brick anyway.  We handed over to Orbit 2 the option to shut down the laptop, but it was not needed.

Log / Entry:PRO REAL-TIME LOG / 2380898Category:Manufacturing DeviceAction:CoordinationFlags:PREP PRO
Author:Mills, Andrew D.E-1 GMT 299 MD Deactivation Timeline Discrepancy
PRO-MD DACT-CMD is scheduled to end at 11:20.
MD-H/W-POWER ends at 11:30. (though it should end at 11:20)
With MD's power band starting on E-0 the power band can not be edited.
MD's Deactivation can not be moved to the right or it would cause a failed crew touch constraint. (45 Minute Touch Temp Constraint)
Workaround: Ignore the extra 10 minutes of power resources and Deactivate MD per the timeline.

Log / Entry:PRO REAL-TIME LOG / 2381305Category:SABL 1Action:ErrorFlags:PRO CMD OFF NOMINAL, New PAIL/PAR, PAR Recurrence (Closed)
Author:Goodman, Daniel S.
SABL1 Fault State Change - Possible New PAR or Recurrence of SABL2-HW-0003 SABL Fault Due to FGBA Failure (Closed)
06:46:03 - [EM] SABL 1 - SABL Status does not equal 0 or 1
06:46:03 - [EM] SABL 1 - SABL Status is a value of 3 (Critical)
06:46:03 - [EM] SABL 1 - SABL State is greater than 3 (Probably a Fault)
EM instructions say "Call the SABL PD". Reported it to POD. OC is calling BioServe.
SABL 1 display shows several parameters out of state (See attached image). The payload also wasn't maintaining its setpoint, and the temperature dropped ~2 degrees over ~10 minutes.

BioServe PD reported to OC that the signature doesn't match anything they've observed before, and instructed us to power OFF the payload until the PD comes on for planned SABL4 activities on O2.
BioServe and OC confirmed that there are no samples in SABL1 and it isn't needed until SpX-24 in December.
POD/FLIGHT are GO for unscheduled SABL1 deactivation.

SABL1 Deactivation
GCP Vol 3 Ann 2 3.7.2 SABL Deactivation
07:21:59 - Disabled power and comm to ER2 L5.
Leaving Thermal Resources in place for potential troubleshooting on O2.
Notified POD.

Additional information: When I searched the logs for this, I discovered that this was similar to PAR SABL2-SW-0011 - State is Greater Than 3 (Probably a Fault) (Closed) with the significant difference that these parameters did not come back within limits a few minutes after. We saw a current drop in NRT at the time these EMs came in from ~1.75A to ~1.3A, and it didn't return to nominal in the ~35 minutes between the anomaly and our deactivation (see second attached image). Reading the PAR SABL2-SW-0011, I discovered that this was already documented in a different far more similar PAR SABL2-HW-0003 - SABL Fault Due To FGBA Failure (Closed) in which we received the same EMs. The solution to this PAR was initially for PRO to perform a power cycle, but all SABL units were updated with a software update by December 2018 that was supposed to recover SABL automatically (hence the creation of SABL2-SW-0011 in which returned SABL to nominal each time). So, I believe SABL1 experienced a fault as a result of an FGBA failure, but for whatever reason the onboard software did not resolve it.
